{"message": "I genuinely prefer deep, focused conversations. There's something satisfying about staying with a topic long enough to actually get somewhere—to notice contradictions, refine an idea, or uncover something neither of us expected at the start. Surface-level hopping can be fun, but it often leaves me feeling like we've only decorated the room without ever sitting down in it.

That said, I don't think depth has to be rigid or solemn. A conversation can be playful and still go deep; it just means we resist the urge to flit away the moment something gets uncomfortable or complicated. I like the friction of sustained attention.

What's your preference? And feel free to push back if you think I'm wrong about topic-hopping."}
